{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2416"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2416"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.06,0.55,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51508"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2416"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36809"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"2838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51508"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with difficulty breathing and a diffuse rash. His parent reports that the patient was at a party and ate \u0027something\u0027. By the time the parent reached him, he was having difficulty breathing and had hives all over his body. The parent also noted that his face appeared swollen. He weighs 20 kg. The boy received one EpiPen Junior 150 mcg from his parent and seven minutes later the paramedics administered a further 0.2 mL of 1:1000 adrenaline intramuscularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the Emergency Department, the boy receives 400 mL of 0.9% sodium chloride to stabilise blood pressure. Three and a half hours after the last adrenaline dose was administered, the boy begins to deteriorate again with hives and widespread bilateral wheeze. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. A further adrenaline bolus of 0.2 mL of 1:1000 adrenaline is administered intramuscularly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management if he does not improve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nebulised 1% adrenaline solution","Nebulised 0.5% salbutamol","400 mL bolus of 0.9% sodium chloride","Intravenous adrenaline infusion","Additional 0.2 mL 1:1000 adrenaline intramuscularly"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of anaphylaxis (e.g., urticaria, difficulty breathing, diffuse bilateral wheezes). Anaphylaxis is a type I hypersensitivity reaction characterized by IgE-mediated cell degranulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGuidelines suggest that if there is an inadequate response after 2-3 adrenaline doses, or deterioration of the patient, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous adrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E should be started, given by staff trained in its use or in liaison with an emergency specialist. IV adrenaline infusions should be used with a dedicated line, infusion pump and anti-reflux valves wherever possible. The patient has normal vital signs for his age and is haemodynamically stable. An adrenaline infusion will help prevent further episodes of anaphylactic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is considered in cases of acute upper airway obstruction which is suggested by swelling or tightness in the throat, difficulty talking, reduced breath sounds or hoarse voice, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBronchodilators such as \u003Cstrong\u003Esalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E are appropriate for persistent wheeze as in this patient, but are not the most appropriate next step in management. Bronchodilators must not be used as first-line medication for anaphylaxis as they do not prevent or relieve upper airway obstruction, hypotension or shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal saline bolus\u003C/strong\u003E (often with glucagon) is considered if patients have persistent shock and/or hypotension. This patient\u0027s blood pressure is within range for his age (80-115 mmHg), although close monitoring is also important for acutely unwell patients. At this stage, further saline bolus is not the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResponse to 0.2 mL of 1:1000 adrenaline administered intramuscularly must first be assessed before giving another \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular bolus of adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E. In this scenario, the patient has already had two doses of adrenaline boluses in addition to the initial EpiPen Junior 150 mcg, and it is therefore more preferable to set up an adrenaline infusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IV adrenaline infusion should be set up after inadequate response after 2-3 adrenaline doses.","Nebulised adrenaline can be used in cases of acute upper airway obstruction in anaphylaxis in addition to other airway management measures.","Nebulised salbutamol is used in anaphylaxis to manage persistent wheeze."],"references":["Anaphylaxis: Emergency management for health professionals. In: Australian prescriber [online]. 2022; accessed 2024 Mar. Available at: https://ccmsfiles.tg.org.au/s3/PDFs/Anaphylaxis-2022-Aust-Prescriber-Anaphylaxis-Wallchart.pdf Last updated 2022.","Anaphylaxis. In: The Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA) [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/anaphylaxis","ASCIA Guidelines - Acute Management of Anaphylaxis. In: The Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA) [online]. 2023; accessed 2023 Dec 10. Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/papers/acute-management-of-anaphylaxis-guidelines","Harding, Mason, Efron. Chapter 3: Resuscitation and Medical Emergencies. In: Paediatric Handbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Ltd. 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2416"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-26T12:34:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-26T12:35:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51508"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"crea